The paper presents a method for learning Bayesian networks from data sets, which is a common topic in machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The focus on treewidth-bounded networks suggests a connection to graph theory and combinatorial optimization (cs.DM). The scalability of the algorithm and its ability to handle large domains and treewidths suggests a connection to database systems (cs.DB). The use of large data sets and the comparison to state-of-the-art methods suggests a connection to statistical learning (cs.LG) and possibly social and information networks (cs.SI).
